Tffls edition, originally undertaken with a view to the requirements of the higher forms of schools‚ has been considerably enlarged in the course of preparation, and now appears on a scale uniform with that of my edition of the Annals. lt even exceeds it in the proportion of commentary to text, and represents a corresponding amount os time and work: but it still needs to be prefaced by an apology sor the incom- pleteness which thorough students will easily detect in it.

lt has been evident to me during my work upon it that the preparation of a really comprehensive edition would require such a knowledge of German archaeology, history, and law, as probably not many Englishmen possess, and which few who have acquired it would care to bring to bear on so limited an object. A sull study would also have to be added of all the minor works and monographs on various points which the national interest in the subject has accumulated and still continues to accumulate in Germany; and an editor who desired duly to gather up and review the results of such research, would have to make his commentary so apparently disproportionate to the bulk os the treatise itself as to repel the majority of students.
